This paper proposes a new approach to learning generative models that can modify certain aspects of the learned distribution while preserving others. This is a topic that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), social and information networks (cs.SI), and computational linguistics (cs.CL). However, given the focus on generative models and the use of the Gromov-Wasserstein distance, which is a tool commonly used in machine learning, we believe that cs.LG is the most likely sub-category.
